nflict since the beginning of warfare. Children and War shows that boys and girls have routinely contributed to home front war efforts, armies have accepted under-aged soldiers for centuries, and war-time experiences have always affected the ways in which grown-up children of war perceive themselves and their societies. The essays in this collection range from explorations of childhood during the American Revolution and of the writings of free black children during the Civil War to children's home front war efforts during World War II, representations of war and defeat in Japanese children's magazines, and growing up in war-torn Liberia. Children and War provides a historical context for two centuries of children's multi-faceted involvement with war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aChildren and war. 7aHISTORY / Military / Wars & Conflicts (Other).2bisacsh1 aBlessing, Benita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCardoza, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Aaron J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColes, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColes, Robert.1 aEriksson, Cynthia B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Jeanine Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffiths, Owen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaskins, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeathorn, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Margaret D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirschenbaum, Lisa A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 